<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-951-410  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 951 410.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Jan 16 1989 v6 n2 p50(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Measuring moods by PC. (personnel management) (BusinessApplications Digest: Human Resources)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Questar Data Systems Inc. (products)Caras and Associates Inc. (products)Team Evaluation and Management Systems (products).andO;Product:   PC-Stargraph (computer program) (usage)Atticomp (Computer program)TEAMS (Computer program).andO;Topic:     Personnel managementHuman Resource Management Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>When a fired employee at a Southern firm complained his supervisors had beenincompetent, top management took action.andP;  They used PC software to devise anemployee questionnaire about the supervisors.andP;  Workers completed the surveyusing PCs to give management a quick consensus on the matter.andM;When the Board of Regents at Arizona State University mandated a merit-paypolicy, administrators turned to a PC-based system that made the appraisalprocess fairer by involving peers for the first time in co-workers'evaluations.andM;A growing number of PC packages are helping firms understand workers'attitudes on everything from the way they work together to how they feelabout corporate policies.andM;Software for measuring attitudes on policies may provide anything from asimple yea-or-nay snapshot on an issue to sophisticated, demographic anaylsesthat rival (or export files into) high-end statistical packages, according toDick Frantzreb, president of Advanced Personnel Systems, a directorypublisher in Roseville, Calif.andM;PC/Stargraph, from Questar Data Systems Inc., of Eagan, Minn., helps managersdevise hard-copy surveys and analyze results on the PC.andP;  The company isworking on an interface for scanning paper surveys into the software foranalysis.andM;Atticomp, from Caras andamp; Associates Inc. of Columbia, Md., helps firms devisesurveys to detect attitude shifts, conducting surveys on the PC.andO;Organizational Universe Survey System, from Organizational Universe Systemsof Glendora, Calif., includes a ''normative database'' that lets firmscompare their problems against others'.andM;Other packages focus on work-group dynamics.andP;  Supersync, new from SwixTechInc. of Irvine, Calif., lets employees indicate whom they really get helpfrom around they office.andP;  Acumen, from Human Factors Advanced TechnologyGroup of San Rafael, Calif., gives managers a glimpse of how workers viewthem.andM;TEAMS, marketed by Team Evaluation and Management Systems of Tempe, Ariz.,andO;lets the opinions of four employee-selected peers shape a supervisor'sevalation.andP;  At Arizona State, claims of unfair employment practices havedeclined to zero since the introduction of TEAMS, according to Mark Edwards,the software's developer.andO;</TEXT></DOC>